00:43:41.814 --> 00:43:44.269
AUDIENCE: What about the
political boundaries,

00:43:44.269 --> 00:43:48.089
the borders of all the vassals?

00:43:48.089 --> 00:43:50.380
JONATHAN ROBERTS: So I think
that would be fascinating.

00:43:50.380 --> 00:43:52.431
I think it's tricky
to figure out.

00:43:52.431 --> 00:43:54.430
In Westeros, that would
probably work quite well

00:43:54.430 --> 00:43:56.732
because you have clear
enough allegiances.

00:43:56.732 --> 00:43:59.190
In the case of the Free Cities,
that gets quite complicated

00:43:59.190 --> 00:44:02.430
because there are--
what's really on the maps

00:44:02.430 --> 00:44:04.510
is the big political
centers, but there's

00:44:04.510 --> 00:44:07.790
so much more in
those grasslands.

00:44:07.790 --> 00:44:10.761
Like the Disputed Lands is a
land of warring baron states,

00:44:10.761 --> 00:44:11.260
I believe.

00:44:11.260 --> 00:44:14.930
So it doesn't get represented
in full detail here.

00:44:14.930 --> 00:44:18.445
But yeah, a political map of
Westeros would be fascinating.

00:44:18.445 --> 00:44:19.945
I think people have
done a few shots

00:44:19.945 --> 00:44:23.420
at that in kind of the
style of the HBO map,

00:44:23.420 --> 00:44:25.560
where they colored blocks
of it like a Risk map

00:44:25.560 --> 00:44:26.820
to say who's controlling
what and where.

00:44:26.820 --> 00:44:28.361
But that's a really
good dynamic map.

00:44:28.361 --> 00:44:30.350
That should be like
taking one of these,

00:44:30.350 --> 00:44:33.330
throwing it up on a nice,
slippy Google Maps layer,

00:44:33.330 --> 00:44:35.650
putting a polygon
there on top of that.

00:44:35.650 --> 00:44:37.935
More than happy to work
on any of the JavaScript

00:44:37.935 --> 00:44:39.435
that needs to go
into that because I

00:44:39.435 --> 00:44:42.312
would love to see that happen.

00:44:42.312 --> 00:44:45.080
AUDIENCE: What
projection do these use?

00:44:45.080 --> 00:44:46.554
Is the world spherical?

00:44:46.554 --> 00:44:47.470
JONATHAN ROBERTS: Yes.

00:44:47.470 --> 00:44:48.410
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:44:48.410 --> 00:44:48.910
Thanks.

00:44:48.910 --> 00:44:50.535
JONATHAN ROBERTS:
Yes, it is spherical.

00:44:50.535 --> 00:44:54.480
And there is no defined
projection for these.

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:57.020
One thing that the really
careful observer will notice

00:44:57.020 --> 00:45:00.330
is that there are compass
roses and lines on these ones.

00:45:00.330 --> 00:45:02.777
They disappear from
the finals [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:02.777 --> 00:45:04.860
These are not-- there's
no mathematical projection

00:45:04.860 --> 00:45:06.810
for these maps.

00:45:06.810 --> 00:45:07.636
Yes.

00:45:07.636 --> 00:45:12.820
AUDIENCE: So the show's showing
Braavos I think next week.

00:45:12.820 --> 00:45:15.682
Do you know if those people who
work on [INAUDIBLE] of the show

00:45:15.682 --> 00:45:18.184
reference your maps,
or if they're just

00:45:18.184 --> 00:45:19.100
doing their own thing?

00:45:19.100 --> 00:45:21.516
JONATHAN ROBERTS: I do know
that the books and the TV show

00:45:21.516 --> 00:45:23.330
are quite distinct properties.

00:45:23.330 --> 00:45:26.390
So for example, when I asked
the question, the two Red Keeps.

00:45:26.390 --> 00:45:28.140
There's one which is
drawn by Ted Nasmith,

00:45:28.140 --> 00:45:28.880
and there's one that
appears in the show,

00:45:28.880 --> 00:45:29.990
and they look
completely different.

00:45:29.990 --> 00:45:31.070
Which should I go with?

00:45:31.070 --> 00:45:33.670
And I was quite clearly told,
go with the Ted Nasmith one.

00:45:33.670 --> 00:45:36.320
That's what it looks like.

00:45:36.320 --> 00:45:39.580
So yeah, I would expect it's
going to be quite different.

00:45:39.580 --> 00:45:41.420
I know that the
Titan is different

00:45:41.420 --> 00:45:45.280
because it turns out he
doesn't have a spear.

00:45:45.280 --> 00:45:47.741
But that was something which
I had failed to find anywhere

00:45:47.741 --> 00:45:49.990
in the books, and we checked
and didn't find anything.

00:45:49.990 --> 00:45:52.710
So I think he has a sword
in the HBO show, though.

00:45:52.710 --> 00:45:54.180
It'll be different,
but I'm going

00:45:54.180 --> 00:45:55.130
to be looking quite carefully.

00:45:55.130 --> 00:45:55.905
It's like, oh.

00:45:55.905 --> 00:45:58.500
How close did they go?

00:45:58.500 --> 00:46:00.150
AUDIENCE: So tricky question.

00:46:00.150 --> 00:46:02.480
Greywater Watch is
a castle that moves.

00:46:02.480 --> 00:46:05.945
Do you have any idea of
the range [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:05.945 --> 00:46:08.420
that it exists in,
or a spatial plane?

00:46:08.420 --> 00:46:10.490
JONATHAN ROBERTS: Yeah,
I don't know that one.

00:46:10.490 --> 00:46:12.292
That one I left
well out of this.

00:46:15.659 --> 00:46:17.990
AUDIENCE: Do you ever
come across-- you

00:46:17.990 --> 00:46:20.010
know how the age of
heroes, they had that lamp

00:46:20.010 --> 00:46:21.690
where supposedly the
First Men crossed.

00:46:21.690 --> 00:46:25.000
Did you have to take that into
account when mapping it out,

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:27.270
what the maesters
of the Citadel would

00:46:27.270 --> 00:46:29.976
have thought it would have
been, or what the remnants of it

00:46:29.976 --> 00:46:30.160
would have been?

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:31.790
JONATHAN ROBERTS: So
that one didn't come in,

00:46:31.790 --> 00:46:33.920
but I'm pretty sure-- well,
my guess would be it's

00:46:33.920 --> 00:46:35.950
related to the Stepstones,
which comes across

00:46:35.950 --> 00:46:38.911
at the very bottom
edge of there.

00:46:38.911 --> 00:46:40.869
AUDIENCE: When you were
going through the books

00:46:40.869 --> 00:46:46.060
and breaking down in relation
to each city and location

00:46:46.060 --> 00:46:48.940
in relation to one another,
did you find any contradictions

00:46:48.940 --> 00:46:51.780
that just-- the way in
which they mapped out

00:46:51.780 --> 00:46:53.760
in the narrative
wouldn't work when

00:46:53.760 --> 00:46:55.480
you were translating to the map?

00:46:55.480 --> 00:46:57.965
And how did you
sort of negotiate

00:46:57.965 --> 00:47:00.857
any of that to try and
actually have it work?

00:47:00.857 --> 00:47:03.190
JONATHAN ROBERTS: There was
one tricky piece in Braavos,

00:47:03.190 --> 00:47:08.610
where there was something that
just wouldn't quite work out.

00:47:08.610 --> 00:47:12.390
I think I shouldn't go into
any more detail-- well, yeah.

00:47:12.390 --> 00:47:15.020
There was a very detailed
conversation there

00:47:15.020 --> 00:47:16.050
basically about it.

00:47:16.050 --> 00:47:18.750
AUDIENCE: --itself, or maybe you
have two different characters

00:47:18.750 --> 00:47:21.710
going to the same location, and
the way in which they describe

00:47:21.710 --> 00:47:25.677
navigating it, it actually
makes it two different places.

00:47:25.677 --> 00:47:27.260
JONATHAN ROBERTS:
So in Braavos, there

00:47:27.260 --> 00:47:29.093
were-- there's lot of
different descriptions

00:47:29.093 --> 00:47:30.305
and lots of different places.

00:47:30.305 --> 00:47:32.180
But it turns out that
it was all loose enough

00:47:32.180 --> 00:47:34.496
that it was possible to find
a consistent way of placing

00:47:34.496 --> 00:47:34.996
everything.

00:47:34.996 --> 00:47:35.614
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:47:35.614 --> 00:47:38.030
JONATHAN ROBERTS: And all of
that got very, very carefully

00:47:38.030 --> 00:47:40.384
cleared because, obviously,
that makes a difference,

00:47:40.384 --> 00:47:42.800
and there was a bunch of Braavos
stuff I had not seen yet.

00:47:42.800 --> 00:47:44.431
AUDIENCE: So you do have
to take a little bit

00:47:44.431 --> 00:47:45.470
of creative liberty.

00:47:45.470 --> 00:47:46.150
JONATHAN ROBERTS:
For Braavos, yeah.

00:47:46.150 --> 00:47:48.660
Everything else was actually
really precisely mapped out.

00:47:48.660 --> 00:47:49.900
Braavos was the one
case where there

00:47:49.900 --> 00:47:52.275
were a lot of locations that
were mentioned that actually

00:47:52.275 --> 00:47:54.321
hadn't turned up
in the sketch yet.

00:47:54.321 --> 00:47:55.855
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:47:55.855 --> 00:47:57.396
AUDIENCE: Is Martin
now going to have

00:47:57.396 --> 00:47:59.642
to write the books to be
consistent with your maps?

00:47:59.642 --> 00:48:02.010
JONATHAN ROBERTS: No.

00:48:02.010 --> 00:48:02.850
Absolutely not.

00:48:02.850 --> 00:48:05.339
And part of that
is because-- this

00:48:05.339 --> 00:48:07.380
is part of the reason for
the projection question

00:48:07.380 --> 00:48:09.379
and part of the reason
for a lot of these things

00:48:09.379 --> 00:48:11.400
is that this, these
are all supposed

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:14.980
to be not even factual in
a fantasy world, factual.

00:48:14.980 --> 00:48:17.473
These are all loose
representations.

00:48:17.473 --> 00:48:19.400
If you look at historical
maps from people

00:48:19.400 --> 00:48:20.900
who had the same
kind of technology,

00:48:20.900 --> 00:48:24.610
they were wildly different
between one map or another.

00:48:24.610 --> 00:48:27.170
This is definitely
supposed to reflect

00:48:27.170 --> 00:48:28.880
that kind of map of the world.

00:48:28.880 --> 00:48:30.338
When you go to the
far east, you've

00:48:30.338 --> 00:48:32.552
got things like City
of the Bloodless Men.

00:48:32.552 --> 00:48:34.990
Who the hell knows what that is?

00:48:34.990 --> 00:48:36.930
But that is the
whole sense of these.

00:48:36.930 --> 00:48:39.860
There's a bunch of this which
is just very, very unknown

00:48:39.860 --> 00:48:41.652
and, yeah.

00:48:41.652 --> 00:48:43.360
These aren't supposed
to be fundamentally

00:48:43.360 --> 00:48:44.940
accurate in the long term.

00:48:44.940 --> 00:48:46.420
And particularly, when
you look at the far east,

00:48:46.420 --> 00:48:47.656
there's a big difference
between how the far east

00:48:47.656 --> 00:48:50.110
was represented in these maps
and how they're represented

00:48:50.110 --> 00:48:51.900
by any of the maps
that come out of HBO.

00:48:51.900 --> 00:48:54.125
It's a completely
different land structure.

00:48:54.125 --> 00:48:56.500
The seas are in different
places, all that kind of stuff.

00:48:56.500 --> 00:48:59.041
Totally consistent with how we
look at our own medieval maps.

00:48:59.041 --> 00:49:03.860
The differences of that scale
were common and ever-present.

00:49:03.860 --> 00:49:08.157
AUDIENCE: How do you decide
on the shape of coastlines?

00:49:08.157 --> 00:49:10.073
JONATHAN ROBERTS: The
shapes of the coastlines

00:49:10.073 --> 00:49:11.810
were actually really
carefully laid out already.

00:49:11.810 --> 00:49:13.080
I mean, they were
smooth pencil lines,

00:49:13.080 --> 00:49:15.371
so they were just broken up
and made a bit more jagged.

00:49:15.371 --> 00:49:18.540
But there are descriptions
down to the individual cliffs

00:49:18.540 --> 00:49:21.185
as to what they are, what they
look like, how jagged they are.

00:49:21.185 --> 00:49:22.560
I got notes back
saying, oh, this

00:49:22.560 --> 00:49:25.870
should be much more like small
islets and islands coming off

00:49:25.870 --> 00:49:26.370
here.

00:49:26.370 --> 00:49:27.703
This should be much more jagged.

00:49:27.703 --> 00:49:29.490
This is a coastline
you can't land in.

00:49:29.490 --> 00:49:30.562
This is smoother.

00:49:30.562 --> 00:49:31.270
This has a beach.

00:49:31.270 --> 00:49:32.910
That beach should be this color.

00:49:32.910 --> 00:49:36.080
We're talking like super
granular responses.

00:49:36.080 --> 00:49:38.991
So I did the closest I
could get with those notes

00:49:38.991 --> 00:49:41.240
I had, and then we went
through iterations, going back

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:43.950
and forth on those kind
of levels of detail.

00:49:43.950 --> 00:49:46.220
Down to the point where
in the final maps,

00:49:46.220 --> 00:49:48.990
there's five different
distinct color and styles

00:49:48.990 --> 00:49:51.882
for farmland across
the world map.

00:49:51.882 --> 00:49:54.340
It's going to be hard to spot
if you don't know it's there,

00:49:54.340 --> 00:49:57.910
but there are specifically five
different layers of farmland.

00:49:57.910 --> 00:49:59.920
So in this world
here, I think, it's

00:49:59.920 --> 00:50:02.497
classified A, B, C,
D, and E. And so those

00:50:02.497 --> 00:50:04.580
were all specifically
different types of farmland,

00:50:04.580 --> 00:50:07.080
to get an idea of the different
arable land around the world.

00:50:07.080 --> 00:50:08.590
When you get that
level of feedback,

00:50:08.590 --> 00:50:12.090
your job gets really easy.

00:50:12.090 --> 00:50:15.978
AUDIENCE: So what part of
this-- I'm just wondering,

00:50:15.978 --> 00:50:18.408
is there a particular part
where it took a very long time,

00:50:18.408 --> 00:50:21.201
collaborating between you and
the editors and George R. R.

00:50:21.201 --> 00:50:23.268
Martin to actually
agree on how to do it,

00:50:23.268 --> 00:50:25.452
as opposed to being put
together, and how it worked?

00:50:25.452 --> 00:50:26.660
JONATHAN ROBERTS: Not really.

00:50:26.660 --> 00:50:30.152
I think from my perspective,
it's impossible to tell,

00:50:30.152 --> 00:50:31.860
like the round trip
time for that message

00:50:31.860 --> 00:50:34.390
was due to at any point.

00:50:34.390 --> 00:50:36.250
The editors were all
working very hard.

00:50:36.250 --> 00:50:38.250
They passed things
on to George when

00:50:38.250 --> 00:50:40.520
it needed to be something
that he decided on.

00:50:40.520 --> 00:50:43.230
And then he went through
this in great detail

00:50:43.230 --> 00:50:45.290
a couple of times
through the process

00:50:45.290 --> 00:50:48.001
to get very granular feedback.

00:50:48.001 --> 00:50:48.500
Yeah.

00:50:48.500 --> 00:50:50.690
Any big project with any
large group of people,

00:50:50.690 --> 00:50:53.410
you get some mental lag
in there for all sorts

00:50:53.410 --> 00:50:54.640
of different reasons.

00:50:54.640 --> 00:50:55.880
Definitely not unexpected.

00:51:00.064 --> 00:51:04.894
AUDIENCE: So the Green Fork of
